data.name: Label1.Text
data.value: Unlike monoalphabetic ciphers (the Caesar cipher), polyalphabetic ciphers are less susceptible to frequency analysis, as more than one letter in the plaintext can be represented by a single letter in the encryption.

data.name: lblCaesarCracking.Text
data.value:
Decryption, or "cracking", is the process of finding a way of obtaining the plaintext from ciphertext without knowing the key.
If we know that a piece of ciphertext was enciphered using the Caesar cipher, the simplest way to retrieve the original plaintext is to simply perform a brute-force attack. Since there are a limited number of possible shifts (26 in English), they can each be tested in turn. We can essentially perform the same Caesar cipher upon the ciphertext, and one of the 26 possible keys will return the plaintext.
A good example of this is the usage of the Caesar cipher with a key of 13 (specifically known as ROT13). Once we encipher plaintext with a key of 13, re-enciphering the ciphertext will result in the original plaintext!

data.name: lblVigenereInfo1.Text
data.value:
The Vigenère cipher is a historical cipher, similar to the Caesar cipher. It is another substitution cipher, where each letter is replaced by a new letter. However, where the Caesar cipher simply replaces each letter by a new letter fixed distance away from it, the Vigenère cipher changes this distance for each letter based on different distances. This makes the Vigenère cipher a "polyalphabetic cipher".
For centuries this type of cipher was thought to be impregnable and was known as “the unbreakable cipher", despite its simplicity, and it remained unbroken until the time of Charles Babbage, a noted mathematician and famously, the "father of the programmable computer".
The Vigenère cipher is strangely misattributed to Blaise de Vigenère, who did however make a contribution to cryptology in the form of a separate cipher, the autokey. The real inventor of the "Vigenère" cipher, Leon Battista Alberti, claimed his invention of the polyalphabetic cipher to be unbreakable and "worthy of kings".

data.name: lblPrintoutExplanation.Text
data.value:
Cut out the paper print-outs and attach the smaller wheel on top of the larger wheel using a split-pin to create a "Caesar cipher wheel".
The outside wheel is the plaintext wheel, while the inside wheel is the ciphertext wheel.
To encipher a message using the wheel, starting with all letters matching up, rotate the inside wheel anti-clockwise by a chosen key. Each letter in the message is replaced with the corresponding letter on the inside wheel.

data.name: lblVigenereInfo3.Text
data.value:
To encipher a message using the Vigenère cipher, firstly devise a key, which is usually a short phrase. Repeat this key so that the length matches the length of the message to be enciphered.
Then, simply use the Vigenère table for each plaintext letter with the corresponding alphabet, by searching for the plaintext letter in the row labelled with the current letter of the key. This new letter is the enciphered version of the plaintext letter.
